The vulnerability stems from an unsafe deserialization flaw within React's "Flight" protocol, which is responsible for handling server component payloads. The server fails to adequately validate incoming data, enabling attackers to inject malicious objects that are then deserialized in privileged server contexts, leading to the execution of arbitrary JavaScript code.

React versions 19.0.0, 19.1.0, 19.1.1, and 19.2.0 are directly impacted, including associated packages like `react-server-dom-parcel`, `react-server-dom-turbopack`, and `react-server-dom-webpack`. Many popular frameworks that utilize React Server Components are also affected, most notably Next.js (versions 15.x and 16.x with App Router, and Canary builds from 14.3.0), React Router, and Waku. Exploitation is possible even under default configurations of these applications.

The vulnerability was publicly disclosed on December 3, 2025. Within hours of its disclosure, active exploitation was observed in the wild, including by multiple China-nexus threat groups such as Earth Lamia and Jackpot Panda. The widespread and rapid exploitation led to its inclusion in the CISA Known Exploited Vulnerabilities Catalog. Post-exploitation activities have included system fingerprinting, privilege verification, network interface mapping, sensitive credential enumeration, and the retrieval of malicious binaries. In some cases, new Linux backdoors like KSwapDoor and Auto-color have been deployed. The flaw has also been leveraged as part of ransomware campaigns.

Immediate patching is crucial to mitigate the risk posed by CVE-2025-55182. Organizations are advised to apply vendor-provided mitigations or discontinue the use of affected products if patches are unavailable."""
